# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pointer-lock
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A **computer mouse** (plural **mice**; rarely **mouses**) is a hand-held pointing device that detects two-dimensional motion relative to a surface.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This motion is typically translated into the motion of the pointer (called a cursor) on a display, which allows a smooth control of the graphical user interface of a computer.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The first public demonstration of a mouse controlling a computer system was done by Douglas Engelbart in 1968 as part of the Mother of All Demos.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Mice originally used two separate wheels to directly track movement across a surface: one in the x-dimension and one in the Y.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Later, the standard design shifted to use a ball rolling on a surface to detect motion, in turn connected to internal rollers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Most modern mice use optical movement detection with no moving parts.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Though originally all mice were connected to a computer by a cable, many modern mice are cordless, relying on short-range radio communication with the connected system.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In addition to moving a cursor, computer mice have one or more buttons to allow operations such as the selection of a menu item on the associated display.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Mice often also feature other elements, such as touch surfaces and scroll wheels, which enable additional control and dimensional input.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The earliest known written use of the term *mouse* in reference to a computer pointing device is in Bill English's July 1965 publication, "Computer-Aided Display Control".
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This likely originated from its resemblance to the shape and size of a mouse, with the cord resembling its tail.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The popularity of wireless mice without cords makes the resemblance less obvious.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] According to Roger Bates, a hardware designer under English, the term also came about because the cursor on the screen was, for an unknown reason, referred to as "CAT" and was seen by the team as if it would be chasing the new desktop device.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The plural for the small rodent is always "mice" in modern usage.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The plural for a computer mouse is either "mice" or "mouses" according to most dictionaries, with "mice" being more common.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The first recorded plural usage is "mice"; the online *Oxford Dictionaries* cites a 1984 use, and earlier uses include J.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Licklider's "The Computer as a Communication Device" of 1968.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The trackball, a related pointing device, was invented in 1946 by Ralph Benjamin as part of a post-World War II-era fire-control radar plotting system called the Comprehensive Display System (CDS).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Benjamin was then working for the British Royal Navy Scientific Service.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Benjamin's project used analog computers to calculate the future position of target aircraft based on several initial input points provided by a user with a joystick.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Benjamin felt that a more elegant input device was needed and invented what they called a "roller ball" for this purpose.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The device was patented in 1947, but only a prototype using a metal ball rolling on two rubber-coated wheels was ever built, and the device was kept as a military secret.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Another early trackball was built by Kenyon Taylor, a British electrical engineer working in collaboration with Tom Cranston and Fred Longstaff.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Taylor was part of the original Ferranti Canada, working on the Royal Canadian Navy's DATAR (Digital Automated Tracking and Resolving) system in 1952.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] DATAR was similar in concept to Benjamin's display.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The trackball used four disks to pick up motion, two each for the X and Y directions.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Several rollers provided mechanical support.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] When the ball was rolled, the pickup discs spun and contacts on their outer rim made periodic contact with wires, producing pulses of output with each movement of the ball.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] By counting the pulses, the physical movement of the ball could be determined.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A digital computer calculated the tracks and sent the resulting data to other ships in a task force using pulse-code modulation radio signals.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This trackball used a standard Canadian five-pin bowling ball.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] It was not patented, since it was a secret military project.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Douglas Engelbart of the Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) has been credited in published books by Thierry Bardini, Paul Ceruzzi, Howard Rheingold, and several others as the inventor of the computer mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Engelbart was also recognized as such in various obituary titles after his death in July 2013.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] By 1963, Engelbart had already established a research lab at SRI, the Augmentation Research Center (ARC), to pursue his objective of developing both hardware and software computer technology to "augment" human intelligence.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] That November, while attending a conference on computer graphics in Reno, Nevada, Engelbart began to ponder how to adapt the underlying principles of the planimeter to inputting X- and Y-coordinate data.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] On 14 November 1963, he first recorded his thoughts in his personal notebook about something he initially called a "bug", which is a "3-point" form could have a "drop point and 2 orthogonal wheels".
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] He wrote that the "bug" would be "easier" and "more natural" to use, and unlike a stylus, it would stay still when let go, which meant it would be "much better for coordination with the keyboard".
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In 1964, Bill English joined ARC, where he helped Engelbart build the first mouse prototype.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] They christened the device the *mouse* as early models had a cord attached to the rear part of the device which looked like a tail, and in turn, resembled the common mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] According to Roger Bates, a hardware designer under English, another reason for choosing this name was because the cursor on the screen was also referred to as "CAT" at this time.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] As noted above, this "mouse" was first mentioned in print in a July 1965 report, on which English was the lead author.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] On 9 December 1968, Engelbart publicly demonstrated the mouse at what would come to be known as The Mother of All Demos.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Engelbart never received any royalties for it, as his employer SRI held the patent, which expired before the mouse became widely used in personal computers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In any event, the invention of the mouse was just a small part of Engelbart's much larger project of augmenting human intellect.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Several other experimental pointing-devices developed for Engelbart's oN-Line System (NLS) exploited different body movements – for example, head-mounted devices attached to the chin or nose.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] One early version was a knee operated device placed under the desk, which kept both hands free for typing.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Ultimately the mouse won out because of its speed and convenience.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The first mouse, a bulky device (pictured) used two potentiometers perpendicular to each other and connected to wheels: the rotation of each wheel translated into motion along one axis.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] At the time of the "Mother of All Demos", Engelbart's group had been using their second-generation, 3-button mouse for about a year.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Based on an even earlier trackball device, the mouse device had been developed by the company in 1966 in what had been a parallel and independent discovery.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] As the name suggests and unlike Engelbart's mouse, the Telefunken model already had a ball (diameter 40 mm, weight 40 g) and two mechanical 4-bit rotational position transducers with Gray code-like states, allowing easy movement in any direction.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The bits remained stable for at least two successive states to relax debouncing requirements.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This arrangement was chosen so that the data could also be transmitted to the TR 86 front-end process computer and over longer distance telex lines with c.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Weighing 465 grams (16.4 oz), the device with a total height of about 7 cm (2.8 in) came in a c.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] 12 cm (4.7 in) diameter hemispherical injection-molded thermoplastic casing featuring one central push button.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] As noted above, the device was based on an earlier trackball-like device (also named **Rollkugel**) that was embedded into radar flight control desks.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This trackball had been originally developed by a team led by Rainer Mallebrein at Telefunken *Konstanz* for the German **Bundesanstalt für Flugsicherung** (Federal Air Traffic Control).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] It was part of the corresponding workstation system SAP 300 and the terminal SIG 3001, which had been designed and developed since 1963.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Development for the TR 440 main frame began in 1965.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This led to the development of the TR 86 process computer system with its SIG 100-86 terminal.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Inspired by a discussion with a university customer, Mallebrein came up with the idea of "reversing" the existing *Rollkugel* trackball into a moveable mouse-like device in 1966, so that customers did not have to be bothered with mounting holes for the earlier trackball device.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The device was finished in early 1968, and together with light pens and trackballs, it was commercially offered as an optional input device for their system starting later that year.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Not all customers opted to buy the device, which added costs of DM 1,500 per piece to the already up to 20-million DM deal for the main frame, of which only a total of 46 systems were sold or leased.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] They were installed at more than 20 German universities including RWTH Aachen, Technische Universität Berlin, University of Stuttgart and Konstanz.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Anecdotal reports claim that Telefunken's attempt to patent the device was rejected by the German Patent Office due to lack of inventiveness.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] For the air traffic control system, the Mallebrein team had already developed a precursor to touch screens in form of an ultrasonic-curtain-based pointing device in front of the display.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In 1970, they developed a device named "Touchinput-*Einrichtung*" ("touch input device") based on a conductively coated glass screen.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Xerox Alto was one of the first computers designed for individual use in 1973 and is regarded as the first modern computer to use a mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The third marketed version of an integrated mouse shipped as a part of a computer and intended for personal computer navigation came with the Xerox 8010 Star in 1981.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] By 1982, the Xerox 8010 was probably the best-known computer with a mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Sun-1 also came with a mouse, and the forthcoming Apple Lisa was rumored to use one, but the peripheral remained obscure; Jack Hawley of The Mouse House reported that one buyer for a large organization believed at first that his company sold lab mice.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Hawley, who manufactured mice for Xerox, stated that "Practically, I have the market all to myself right now"; a Hawley mouse cost $415.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In 1982, Logitech introduced the P4 Mouse at the Comdex trade show in Las Vegas, its first hardware mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] That same year Microsoft made the decision to make the MS-DOS program Microsoft Word mouse-compatible, and developed the first PC-compatible mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Microsoft Mouse shipped in 1983, thus beginning the Microsoft Hardware division of the company.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] However, the mouse remained relatively obscure until the appearance of the Macintosh 128K (which included an updated version of the single-button Lisa Mouse) in 1984, and of the Amiga 1000 and the Atari ST in 1985.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A mouse typically controls the motion of a pointer in two dimensions in a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The mouse turns movements of the hand backward and forward, left and right into equivalent electronic signals that in turn are used to move the pointer.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The relative movements of the mouse on the surface are applied to the position of the pointer on the screen, which signals the point where actions of the user take place, so hand movements are replicated by the pointer.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Clicking or pointing (stopping movement while the cursor is within the bounds of an area) can select files, programs or actions from a list of names, or (in graphical interfaces) through small images called "icons" and other elements.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] For example, a text file might be represented by a picture of a paper notebook and clicking while the cursor points at this icon might cause a text editing program to open the file in a window.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Gestural interfaces have become an integral part of modern computing, allowing users to interact with their devices in a more intuitive and natural way.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In addition to traditional pointing-and-clicking actions, users can now employ gestural inputs to issue commands or perform specific actions.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] These stylized motions of the mouse cursor, known as "gestures", have the potential to enhance user experience and streamline workflow.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] To illustrate the concept of gestural interfaces, let's consider a drawing program as an example.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In this scenario, a user can employ a gesture to delete a shape on the canvas.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] By rapidly moving the mouse cursor in an "x" motion over the shape, the user can trigger the command to delete the selected shape.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This gesture-based interaction enables users to perform actions quickly and efficiently without relying solely on traditional input methods.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] While gestural interfaces offer a more immersive and interactive user experience, they also present challenges.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] One of the primary difficulties lies in the requirement of finer motor control from users.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Gestures demand precise movements, which can be more challenging for individuals with limited dexterity or those who are new to this mode of interaction.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] However, despite these challenges, gestural interfaces have gained popularity due to their ability to simplify complex tasks and improve efficiency.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Several gestural conventions have become widely adopted, making them more accessible to users.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] One such convention is the drag and drop gesture, which has become pervasive across various applications and platforms.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The drag and drop gesture is a fundamental gestural convention that enables users to manipulate objects on the screen seamlessly.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Moving the cursor to a different location while holding the button down.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Releasing the mouse button to complete the action.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This gesture allows users to transfer or rearrange objects effortlessly.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] For instance, a user can drag and drop a picture representing a file onto an image of a trash can, indicating the intention to delete the file.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This intuitive and visual approach to interaction has become synonymous with organizing digital content and simplifying file management tasks.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In addition to the drag and drop gesture, several other semantic gestures have emerged as standard conventions within the gestural interface paradigm.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] These gestures serve specific purposes and contribute to a more intuitive user experience.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] These standard semantic gestures, along with the drag and drop convention, form the building blocks of gestural interfaces, allowing users to interact with digital content using intuitive and natural movements.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] At the end of 20th century, digitizer mice (puck) with magnifying glass was used with AutoCAD for the digitizations of blueprints.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Other uses of the mouse's input occur commonly in special application domains.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In interactive three-dimensional graphics, the mouse's motion often translates directly into changes in the virtual objects' or camera's orientation.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] For example, in the first-person shooter genre of games (see below), players usually employ the mouse to control the direction in which the virtual player's "head" faces: moving the mouse up will cause the player to look up, revealing the view above the player's head.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A related function makes an image of an object rotate so that all sides can be examined.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] 3D design and animation software often modally chord many different combinations to allow objects and cameras to be rotated and moved through space with the few axes of movement mice can detect.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] When mice have more than one button, the software may assign different functions to each button.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Often, the primary (leftmost in a right-handed configuration) button on the mouse will select items, and the secondary (rightmost in a right-handed) button will bring up a menu of alternative actions applicable to that item.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The German company Telefunken published on their early ball mouse on 2 October 1968.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Telefunken's mouse was sold as optional equipment for their computer systems.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Bill English, builder of Engelbart's original mouse, created a ball mouse in 1972 while working for Xerox PARC.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The ball mouse replaced the external wheels with a single ball that could rotate in any direction.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] It came as part of the hardware package of the Xerox Alto computer.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Perpendicular chopper wheels housed inside the mouse's body chopped beams of light on the way to light sensors, thus detecting in their turn the motion of the ball.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This variant of the mouse resembled an inverted trackball and became the predominant form used with personal computers throughout the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Xerox PARC group also settled on the modern technique of using both hands to type on a full-size keyboard and grabbing the mouse when required.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The ball mouse has two freely rotating rollers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] One roller detects the forward-backward motion of the mouse and the other the left-right motion.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Opposite the two rollers is a third one (white, in the photo, at 45 degrees) that is spring-loaded to push the ball against the other two rollers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Each roller is on the same shaft as an encoder wheel that has slotted edges; the slots interrupt infrared light beams to generate electrical pulses that represent wheel movement.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Each wheel's disc has a pair of light beams, located so that a given beam becomes interrupted or again starts to pass light freely when the other beam of the pair is about halfway between changes.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Simple logic circuits interpret the relative timing to indicate which direction the wheel is rotating.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This incremental rotary encoder scheme is sometimes called quadrature encoding of the wheel rotation, as the two optical sensors produce signals that are in approximately quadrature phase.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The mouse sends these signals to the computer system via the mouse cable, directly as logic signals in very old mice such as the Xerox mice, and via a data-formatting IC in modern mice.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The driver software in the system converts the signals into motion of the mouse cursor along X and Y axes on the computer screen.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The ball is mostly steel, with a precision spherical rubber surface.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The weight of the ball, given an appropriate working surface under the mouse, provides a reliable grip so the mouse's movement is transmitted accurately.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Ball mice and wheel mice were manufactured for Xerox by Jack Hawley, doing business as The Mouse House in Berkeley, California, starting in 1975.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Based on another invention by Jack Hawley, proprietor of the Mouse House, Honeywell produced another type of mechanical mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Instead of a ball, it had two wheels rotating at off axes.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Key Tronic later produced a similar product.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Modern computer mice took form at the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) under the inspiration of Professor Jean-Daniel Nicoud and at the hands of engineer and watchmaker André Guignard.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This new design incorporated a single hard rubber mouseball and three buttons, and remained a common design until the mainstream adoption of the scroll-wheel mouse during the 1990s.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In 1985, René Sommer added a microprocessor to Nicoud's and Guignard's design.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Through this innovation, Sommer is credited with inventing a significant component of the mouse, which made it more "intelligent"; though optical mice from Mouse Systems had incorporated microprocessors by 1984.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Another type of mechanical mouse, the "analog mouse" (now generally regarded as obsolete), uses potentiometers rather than encoder wheels, and is typically designed to be plug compatible with an analog joystick.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The "Color Mouse", originally marketed by RadioShack for their Color Computer (but also usable on MS-DOS machines equipped with analog joystick ports, provided the software accepted joystick input) was the best-known example.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Early optical mice relied entirely on one or more light-emitting diodes (LEDs) and an imaging array of photodiodes to detect movement relative to the underlying surface, eschewing the internal moving parts a mechanical mouse uses in addition to its optics.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A laser mouse is an optical mouse that uses coherent (laser) light.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The earliest optical mice detected movement on pre-printed mousepad surfaces, whereas the modern LED optical mouse works on most opaque diffuse surfaces; it is usually unable to detect movement on specular surfaces like polished stone.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Laser diodes provide good resolution and precision, improving performance on opaque specular surfaces.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Later, more surface-independent optical mice use an optoelectronic sensor (essentially, a tiny low-resolution video camera) to take successive images of the surface on which the mouse operates.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Battery powered, wireless optical mice flash the LED intermittently to save power, and only glow steadily when movement is detected.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Often called "air mice" since they do not require a surface to operate, inertial mice use a tuning fork or other accelerometer (US Patent 4787051) to detect rotary movement for every axis supported.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The most common models (manufactured by Logitech and Gyration) work using 2 degrees of rotational freedom and are insensitive to spatial translation.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The user requires only small wrist rotations to move the cursor, reducing user fatigue or "gorilla arm".
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Usually cordless, they often have a switch to deactivate the movement circuitry between use, allowing the user freedom of movement without affecting the cursor position.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A patent for an inertial mouse claims that such mice consume less power than optically based mice, and offer increased sensitivity, reduced weight and increased ease-of-use.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In combination with a wireless keyboard an inertial mouse can offer alternative ergonomic arrangements which do not require a flat work surface, potentially alleviating some types of repetitive motion injuries related to workstation posture.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A 3D mouse is a computer input device for viewport interaction with at least three degrees of freedom (DoF), e.g. in 3D computer graphics software for manipulating virtual objects, navigating in the viewport, defining camera paths, posing, and desktop motion capture.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] 3D mice can also be used as spatial controllers for video game interaction, e.g.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] To perform such different tasks the used transfer function and the device stiffness are essential for efficient interaction.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The virtual motion is connected to the 3D mouse control handle via a transfer function.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Position control means that the virtual position and orientation is proportional to the mouse handle's deflection whereas velocity control means that translation and rotation velocity of the controlled object is proportional to the handle deflection.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Ware and Osborne performed an experiment investigating these metaphors whereby it was shown that there is no single best metaphor.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] For manipulation tasks, the object-in-hand metaphor was superior, whereas for navigation tasks the camera-in-hand metaphor was superior.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Logitech 3D Mouse (1990) was the first ultrasonic mouse and is an example of an isotonic 3D mouse having six degrees of freedom (6DoF).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Isotonic devices have also been developed with less than 6DoF, e.g. the Inspector at Technical University of Denmark (5DoF input).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Other examples of isotonic 3D mice are motion controllers, i.e. is a type of game controller that typically uses accelerometers to track motion.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Motion tracking systems are also used for motion capture e.g. in the film industry, although that these tracking systems are not 3D mice in a strict sense, because motion capture only means recording 3D motion and not 3D interaction.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Early 3D mice for velocity control were almost ideally isometric, e.g.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] SpaceBall 1003, 2003, 3003, and a device developed at Deutsches Zentrum für Luft und Raumfahrt (DLR), cf.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] At DLR an elastic 6DoF sensor was developed that was used in Logitech's SpaceMouse and in the products of 3DConnexion.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] SpaceBall 4000 FLX has a maximum deflection of approximately 3 mm (0.12 in) at a maximum force of approximately 10N, that is, a stiffness of approximately 33 N/cm (19 lbf/in).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] SpaceMouse has a maximum deflection of 1.5 mm (0.059 in) at a maximum force of 4.4 N (0.99 lbf), that is, a stiffness of approximately 30 N/cm (17 lbf/in).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Taking this development further, the softly elastic Sundinlabs SpaceCat was developed.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] SpaceCat has a maximum translational deflection of approximately 15 mm (0.59 in) and maximum rotational deflection of approximately 30° at a maximum force less than 2N, that is, a stiffness of approximately 1.3 N/cm (0.74 lbf/in).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] With SpaceCat Sundin and Fjeld reviewed five comparative experiments performed with different device stiffness and transfer functions and performed a further study comparing 6DoF softly elastic position control with 6DoF stiffly elastic velocity control in a positioning task.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] They concluded that for positioning tasks position control is to be preferred over velocity control.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] 3DConnexion's 3D mice have been commercially successful over decades.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] They are used in combination with the conventional mouse for CAD.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Space Mouse is used to orient the target object or change the viewpoint with the non-dominant hand, whereas the dominant hand operates the computer mouse for conventional CAD GUI operation.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This is a kind of space-multiplexed input where the 6 DoF input device acts as a graspable user interface that is always connected to the view port.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] With force feedback the device stiffness can dynamically be adapted to the task just performed by the user, e.g. performing positioning tasks with less stiffness than navigation tasks.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In 2000, Logitech introduced a "tactile mouse" known as the "iFeel Mouse" developed by Immersion Corporation that contained a small actuator to enable the mouse to generate simulated physical sensations.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Such a mouse can augment user-interfaces with haptic feedback, such as giving feedback when crossing a window boundary.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The ability to surf the internet by touch-enabled mouse was first developed in 1996 and first implemented commercially by the Wingman Force Feedback Mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] It requires the user to be able to feel depth or hardness; this ability was realized with the first electrorheological tactile mice but never marketed.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Tablet digitizers are sometimes used with accessories called pucks, devices which rely on absolute positioning, but can be configured for sufficiently mouse-like relative tracking that they are sometimes marketed as mice.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] As the name suggests, this type of mouse is intended to provide optimum comfort and avoid injuries such as carpal tunnel syndrome, arthritis, and other repetitive strain injuries.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] It is designed to fit natural hand position and movements, to reduce discomfort.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] When holding a typical mouse, the ulna and radius bones on the arm are crossed.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some designs attempt to place the palm more vertically, so the bones take more natural parallel position.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Increasing mouse height and angling the mouse topcase can improve wrist posture without negatively affecting performance.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some limit wrist movement, encouraging arm movement instead, that may be less precise but more optimal from the health point of view.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A mouse may be angled from the thumb downward to the opposite side – this is known to reduce wrist pronation.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] However such optimizations make the mouse right or left hand specific, making more problematic to change the tired hand.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Another solution is a pointing bar device.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The so-called *roller bar mouse* is positioned snugly in front of the keyboard, thus allowing bi-manual accessibility.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] These mice are specifically designed for use in computer games.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] They typically employ a wider array of controls and buttons and have designs that differ radically from traditional mice.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] They may also have decorative monochrome or programmable RGB LED lighting.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The additional buttons can often be used for changing the sensitivity of the mouse or they can be assigned (programmed) to macros (i.e., for opening a program or for use instead of a key combination).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] It is also common for game mice, especially those designed for use in real-time strategy games such as *StarCraft*, or in multiplayer online battle arena games such as League of Legends to have a relatively high sensitivity, measured in dots per inch (DPI), which can be as high as 25,600.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] DPI and CPI are the same values that refer to the mouse's sensitivity.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] DPI is a misnomer used in the gaming world, and many manufacturers use it to refer to CPI, counts per inch.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some advanced mice from gaming manufacturers also allow users to adjust the weight of the mouse by adding or subtracting weights to allow for easier control.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Ergonomic quality is also an important factor in gaming mouse, as extended gameplay times may render further use of the mouse to be uncomfortable.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some mice have been designed to have adjustable features such as removable and/or elongated palm rests, horizontally adjustable thumb rests and pinky rests.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some mice may include several different rests with their products to ensure comfort for a wider range of target consumers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Claw Grip: palm rests on the mouse, bent fingers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Finger-Tip Grip: bent fingers, palm does not touch the mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] To transmit their input, typical cabled mice use a thin electrical cord terminating in a standard connector, such as RS-232C, PS/2, ADB, or USB.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Cordless mice instead transmit data via infrared radiation (see IrDA) or radio (including Bluetooth), although many such cordless interfaces are themselves connected through the aforementioned wired serial buses.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] While the electrical interface and the format of the data transmitted by commonly available mice is currently standardized on USB, in the past it varied between different manufacturers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A bus mouse used a dedicated interface card for connection to an IBM PC or compatible computer.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Mouse use in DOS applications became more common after the introduction of the Microsoft Mouse, largely because Microsoft provided an open standard for communication between applications and mouse driver software.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Thus, any application written to use the Microsoft standard could use a mouse with a driver that implements the same API, even if the mouse hardware itself was incompatible with Microsoft's.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This driver provides the state of the buttons and the distance the mouse has moved in units that its documentation calls "mickeys".
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In the 1970s, the Xerox Alto mouse, and in the 1980s the Xerox optical mouse, used a quadrature-encoded X and Y interface.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] This two-bit encoding per dimension had the property that only one bit of the two would change at a time, like a Gray code or Johnson counter, so that the transitions would not be misinterpreted when asynchronously sampled.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The 1985 Sun-3 workstations would ship with a ball based, bus mouse, connected via an 3 pin mini din socket.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Sun later replacing the ball for an optical mechanism dependent on a patterned, reflective, metallic mouse mat, with their type M4 mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The earliest mass-market mice, such as the original Macintosh, Amiga, and Atari ST mice used a D-subminiature 9-pin connector to send the quadrature-encoded X and Y axis signals directly, plus one pin per mouse button.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The mouse was a simple optomechanical device, and the decoding circuitry was all in the main computer.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The 1987 Acorn Archimedes line kept the quadrature-encoded mice of the 68000 computers, and the aftermarket mice sold for 8-bit home computers, like the AMX Mouse, but opted for its own propriety 9 pin mini din connector.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Because the IBM PC did not have a quadrature decoder built in, early PC mice used the RS-232C serial port to communicate encoded mouse movements, as well as provide power to the mouse's circuits.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Mouse Systems Corporation (MSC) version used a five-byte protocol and supported three buttons.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Microsoft version used a three-byte protocol and supported two buttons.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Due to the incompatibility between the two protocols, some manufacturers sold serial mice with a mode switch: "PC" for MSC mode, "MS" for Microsoft mode.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In 1986 Apple first implemented the Apple Desktop Bus allowing the daisy chaining of up to 16 devices, including mice and other devices on the same bus with no configuration whatsoever.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Featuring only a single data pin, the bus used a purely polled approach to device communications and survived as the standard on mainstream models (including a number of non-Apple workstations) until 1998 when Apple's iMac line of computers joined the industry-wide switch to using USB.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Beginning with the Bronze Keyboard PowerBook G3 in May 1999, Apple dropped the external ADB port in favor of USB, but retained an internal ADB connection in the PowerBook G4 for communication with its built-in keyboard and trackpad until early 2005.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] With the arrival of the IBM PS/2 personal-computer series in 1987, IBM introduced the eponymous PS/2 port for mice and keyboards, which other manufacturers rapidly adopted.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The most visible change was the use of a round 6-pin mini-DIN, in lieu of the former 5-pin MIDI style full sized DIN 41524 connector.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In default mode (called *stream mode*) a PS/2 mouse communicates motion, and the state of each button, by means of 3-byte packets.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Here, XS and YS represent the sign bits of the movement vectors, XV and YV indicate an overflow in the respective vector component, and LB, MB and RB indicate the status of the left, middle and right mouse buttons (1 = pressed).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] PS/2 mice also understand several commands for reset and self-test, switching between different operating modes, and changing the resolution of the reported motion vectors.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] A Microsoft IntelliMouse relies on an extension of the PS/2 protocol: the ImPS/2 or IMPS/2 protocol (the abbreviation combines the concepts of "IntelliMouse" and "PS/2").
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] It initially operates in standard PS/2 format, for backward compatibility.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] After the host sends a special command sequence, it switches to an extended format in which a fourth byte carries information about wheel movements.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The IntelliMouse Explorer works analogously, with the difference that its 4-byte packets also allow for two additional buttons (for a total of five).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Mouse vendors also use other extended formats, often without providing public documentation.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The Typhoon mouse uses 6-byte packets which can appear as a sequence of two standard 3-byte packets, such that an ordinary PS/2 driver can handle them.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] For 3D (or 6-degree-of-freedom) input, vendors have made many extensions both to the hardware and to software.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In the late 1990s, Logitech created ultrasound based tracking which gave 3D input to a few millimeters accuracy, which worked well as an input device but failed as a profitable product.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] In 2008, Motion4U introduced its "OptiBurst" system using IR tracking for use as a Maya (graphics software) plugin.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Almost all wired mice today use USB and the USB human interface device class for communication.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Cordless or wireless mice transmit data via radio.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some mice connect to the computer through Bluetooth or Wi-Fi, while others use a receiver that plugs into the computer, for example through a USB port.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Many mice that use a USB receiver have a storage compartment for it inside the mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some "nano receivers" are designed to be small enough to remain plugged into a laptop during transport, while still being large enough to easily remove.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] MS-DOS and Windows 1.0 support connecting a mouse such as a Microsoft Mouse via multiple interfaces: BallPoint, Bus (InPort), Serial port or PS/2.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Windows 98 added built-in support for USB Human Interface Device class (USB HID), with native vertical scrolling support.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Windows 2000 and Windows Me expanded this built-in support to 5-button mice.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Windows XP Service Pack 2 introduced a Bluetooth stack, allowing Bluetooth mice to be used without any USB receivers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Windows Vista added native support for horizontal scrolling and standardized wheel movement granularity for finer scrolling.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Windows 8 introduced BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy) mouse/HID support.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Some systems allow two or more mice to be used at once as input devices.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Late-1980s era home computers such as the Amiga used this to allow computer games with two players interacting on the same computer (Lemmings and The Settlers for example).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The same idea is sometimes used in collaborative software, e.g. to simulate a whiteboard that multiple users can draw on without passing a single mouse around.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Microsoft Windows, since Windows 98, has supported multiple simultaneous pointing devices.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Because Windows only provides a single screen cursor, using more than one device at the same time requires cooperation of users or applications designed for multiple input devices.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Multiple mice are often used in multi-user gaming in addition to specially designed devices that provide several input interfaces.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Windows also has full support for multiple input/mouse configurations for multi-user environments.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] Starting with Windows XP, Microsoft introduced an SDK for developing applications that allow multiple input devices to be used at the same time with independent cursors and independent input points.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] However, it no longer appears to be available.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The introduction of Windows Vista and Microsoft Surface (now known as Microsoft PixelSense) introduced a new set of input APIs that were adopted into Windows 7, allowing for 50 points/cursors, all controlled by independent users.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] The new input points provide traditional mouse input; however, they were designed with other input technologies like touch and image in mind.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] They inherently offer 3D coordinates along with pressure, size, tilt, angle, mask, and even an image bitmap to see and recognize the input point/object on the screen.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] As of 2009, Linux distributions and other operating systems that use X.Org, such as OpenSolaris and FreeBSD, support 255 cursors/input points through Multi-Pointer X.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] However, currently no window managers support Multi-Pointer X leaving it relegated to custom software usage.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p01] There have also been propositions of having a single operator use two mice simultaneously as a more sophisticated means of controlling various graphics and multimedia applications.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Mouse buttons are microswitches which can be pressed to select or interact with an element of a graphical user interface, producing a distinctive clicking sound.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Since around the late 1990s, the three-button scrollmouse has become the de facto standard.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Users most commonly employ the second button to invoke a contextual menu in the computer's software user interface, which contains options specifically tailored to the interface element over which the mouse cursor currently sits.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] By default, the primary mouse button sits located on the left-hand side of the mouse, for the benefit of right-handed users; left-handed users can usually reverse this configuration via software.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Nearly all mice now have an integrated input primarily intended for scrolling on top, usually a single-axis digital wheel or rocker switch which can also be depressed to act as a third button.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Though less common, many mice instead have two-axis inputs such as a tiltable wheel, trackball, or touchpad.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Those with a trackball may be designed to stay stationary, using the trackball instead of moving the mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Mickeys per second is a unit of measurement for the speed and movement direction of a computer mouse, where direction is often expressed as "horizontal" versus "vertical" mickey count.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] However, speed can also refer to the ratio between how many pixels the cursor moves on the screen and how far the mouse moves on the mouse pad, which may be expressed as pixels per mickey, pixels per inch, or pixels per centimeter.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The computer industry often measures mouse sensitivity in terms of counts per inch (CPI), commonly expressed as dots per inch (DPI) – the number of steps the mouse will report when it moves one inch.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In early mice, this specification was called pulses per inch (ppi).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The mickey originally referred to one of these counts, or one resolvable step of motion.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] If the default mouse-tracking condition involves moving the cursor by one screen-pixel or dot on-screen per reported step, then the CPI does equate to DPI: dots of cursor motion per inch of mouse motion.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The CPI or DPI as reported by manufacturers depends on how they make the mouse; the higher the CPI, the faster the cursor moves with mouse movement.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] However, operating system and application software can adjust the mouse sensitivity, making the cursor move faster or slower than its CPI.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] As of 2007, software can change the speed of the cursor dynamically, taking into account the mouse's absolute speed and the movement from the last stop-point.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] For simple software, when the mouse starts to move, the software will count the number of "counts" or "mickeys" received from the mouse and will move the cursor across the screen by that number of pixels (or multiplied by a rate factor, typically less than 1).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The cursor will move slowly on the screen, with good precision.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] When the movement of the mouse passes the value set for some threshold, the software will start to move the cursor faster, with a greater rate factor.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Usually, the user can set the value of the second rate factor by changing the "acceleration" setting.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Operating systems sometimes apply acceleration, referred to as "ballistics", to the motion reported by the mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] For example, versions of Windows prior to Windows XP doubled reported values above a configurable threshold, and then optionally doubled them again above a second configurable threshold.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] These doublings applied separately in the X and Y directions, resulting in very nonlinear response.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Engelbart's original mouse did not require a mousepad; the mouse had two large wheels which could roll on virtually any surface.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] However, most subsequent mechanical mice starting with the steel roller ball mouse have required a mousepad for optimal performance.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The mousepad, the most common mouse accessory, appears most commonly in conjunction with mechanical mice, because to roll smoothly the ball requires more friction than common desk surfaces usually provide.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] So-called "hard mousepads" for gamers or optical/laser mice also exist.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Most optical and laser mice do not require a pad, the notable exception being early optical mice which relied on a grid on the pad to detect movement (e.g.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Whether to use a hard or soft mousepad with an optical mouse is largely a matter of personal preference.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] One exception occurs when the desk surface creates problems for the optical or laser tracking, for example, a transparent or reflective surface, such as glass.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Some mice also come with small "pads" attached to the bottom surface, also called mouse feet or mouse skates, that help the user slide the mouse smoothly across surfaces.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Around 1981, Xerox included mice with its Xerox Star, based on the mouse used in the 1970s on the Alto computer at Xerox PARC.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Sun Microsystems, Symbolics, Lisp Machines Inc., and Tektronix also shipped workstations with mice, starting in about 1981.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Later, inspired by the Star, Apple Computer released the Apple Lisa, which also used a mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] However, none of these products achieved large-scale success.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Only with the release of the Apple Macintosh in 1984 did the mouse see widespread use.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The Macintosh design, commercially successful and technically influential, led many other vendors to begin producing mice or including them with their other computer products (by 1986, Atari ST, Amiga, Windows 1.0, GEOS for the Commodore 64, and the Apple IIGS).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The widespread adoption of graphical user interfaces in the software of the 1980s and 1990s made mice all but indispensable for controlling computers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In November 2008, Logitech built their billionth mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The device often functions as an interface for PC-based computer games and sometimes for video game consoles.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The Classic Mac OS Desk Accessory *Puzzle* in 1984 was the first game designed specifically for a mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] FPSs naturally lend themselves to separate and simultaneous control of the player's movement and aim, and on computers this has traditionally been achieved with a combination of keyboard and mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Players use the X-axis of the mouse for looking (or turning) left and right, and the Y-axis for looking up and down; the keyboard is used for movement and supplemental inputs.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Many shooting genre players prefer a mouse over a gamepad analog stick because the wide range of motion offered by a mouse allows for faster and more varied control.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Although an analog stick allows the player more granular control, it is poor for certain movements, as the player's input is relayed based on a vector of both the stick's direction and magnitude.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Thus, a small but fast movement (known as "flick-shotting") using a gamepad requires the player to quickly move the stick from its rest position to the edge and back again in quick succession, a difficult maneuver.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In addition the stick also has a finite magnitude; if the player is currently using the stick to move at a non-zero velocity their ability to increase the rate of movement of the camera is further limited based on the position their displaced stick was already at before executing the maneuver.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The effect of this is that a mouse is well suited not only to small, precise movements but also to large, quick movements and immediate, responsive movements; all of which are important in shooter gaming.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] This advantage also extends in varying degrees to similar game styles such as third-person shooters.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Some incorrectly ported games or game engines have acceleration and interpolation curves which unintentionally produce excessive, irregular, or even negative acceleration when used with a mouse instead of their native platform's non-mouse default input device.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Depending on how deeply hardcoded this misbehavior is, internal user patches or external 3rd-party software may be able to fix it.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Individual game engines will also have their own sensitivities.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] This often restricts one from taking a game's existing sensitivity, transferring it to another, and acquiring the same 360 rotational measurements.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] A sensitivity converter is the preferred tool that FPS gamers use to translate correctly the rotational movements between different mice and between different games.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Calculating the conversion values manually is also possible but it is more time-consuming and requires performing complex mathematical calculations, while using a sensitivity converter is a lot faster and easier for gamers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Due to their similarity to the WIMP desktop metaphor interface for which mice were originally designed, and to their own tabletop game origins, computer strategy games are most commonly played with mice.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In particular, real-time strategy and MOBA games usually require the use of a mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The left button usually controls primary fire.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] If the game supports multiple fire modes, the right button often provides secondary fire from the selected weapon.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Games with only a single fire mode will generally map secondary fire to *aim down the weapon sights*.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In some games, the right button may also invoke accessories for a particular weapon, such as allowing access to the scope of a sniper rifle or allowing the mounting of a bayonet or silencer.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Players can use a scroll wheel for changing weapons (or for controlling scope-zoom magnification, in older games).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] On most first person shooter games, programming may also assign more functions to additional buttons on mice with more than three controls.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] A keyboard usually controls movement (for example, WASD for moving forward, left, backward, and right, respectively) and other functions such as changing posture.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Since the mouse serves for aiming, a mouse that tracks movement accurately and with less lag (latency) will give a player an advantage over players with less accurate or slower mice.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In some cases the right mouse button may be used to move the player forward, either in lieu of, or in conjunction with the typical WASD configuration.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Many games provide players with the option of mapping their own choice of a key or button to a certain control.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] An early technique of players, circle strafing, saw a player continuously strafing while aiming and shooting at an opponent by walking in circle around the opponent with the opponent at the center of the circle.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Players could achieve this by holding down a key for strafing while continuously aiming the mouse toward the opponent.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Games using mice for input are so popular that many manufacturers make mice specifically for gaming.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Such mice may feature adjustable weights, high-resolution optical or laser components, additional buttons, ergonomic shape, and other features such as adjustable CPI.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Mouse Bungees are typically used with gaming mice because it eliminates the annoyance of the cable.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] This control system resembles that of aircraft control sticks, where pulling back causes pitch up and pushing forward causes pitch down; computer joysticks also typically emulate this control-configuration.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] After id Software's commercial hit of *Doom*, which did not support vertical aiming, competitor Bungie's *Marathon* became the first first-person shooter to support using the mouse to aim up and down.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Games using the Build engine had an option to invert the Y-axis.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The "invert" feature actually made the mouse behave in a manner that users now regard as non-inverted (by default, moving mouse forward resulted in looking down).
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Soon after, id Software released *Quake*, which introduced the invert feature as users now know it.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In 1988, the VTech Socrates educational video game console featured a wireless mouse with an attached mouse pad as an optional controller used for some games.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] In the early 1990s, the Super Nintendo Entertainment System video game system featured a mouse in addition to its controllers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] A mouse was also released for the Nintendo 64, although it was only released in Japan.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] The 1992 game *Mario Paint* in particular used the mouse's capabilities, as did its Japanese-only successor *Mario Artist* on the N64 for its 64DD disk drive peripheral in 1999.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Sega released official mice for their Genesis/Mega Drive, Saturn and Dreamcast consoles.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] NEC sold official mice for its PC Engine and PC-FX consoles.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Sony released an official mouse product for the PlayStation console, included one along with the Linux for PlayStation 2 kit, as well as allowing owners to use virtually any USB mouse with the PS2, PS3, and PS4.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Nintendo's Wii also had this feature implemented in a later software update, and this support was retained on its successor, the Wii U.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] Microsoft's Xbox line of game consoles (which used operaring systems based on modified versions of Windows NT) also had universal-wide mouse support using USB.
[src:pointer-lock/mouse-computing-p02] On June 5, 2025, Nintendo released the Joy-Con 2 controller, a gaming controller with mouse control for the Nintendo Switch 2.
[src:pointer-lock/mouseevent-movementx] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:pointer-lock/mouseevent-movementx] The **`movementX`** read-only property of the `MouseEvent` interface provides the difference in the X coordinate of the mouse (or pointer) between the given move event and the previous move event of the same type.
[src:pointer-lock/mouseevent-movementx] In other words, the value of the property is computed like this: `currentEvent.movementX = currentEvent.screenX - previousEvent.screenX`.
[src:pointer-lock/mouseevent-movementx] The value is zero for all events other than `mousemove`, `pointermove`, and `pointerrawupdate`.
[src:pointer-lock/mouseevent-movementx] Always zero on any `MouseEvent` other than `mousemove`, and any `PointerEvent` other than `pointermove` or `pointerrawupdate`.
[src:pointer-lock/mouseevent-movementx] This example logs the amount of mouse movement using `movementX` and `movementY`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The **Pointer Lock API** (formerly called *Mouse Lock API*) provides input methods based on the movement of the mouse over time (i.e., deltas), not just the absolute position of the mouse cursor in the viewport.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] It gives you access to raw mouse movement, locks the target of mouse events to a single element, eliminates limits on how far mouse movement can go in a single direction, and removes the cursor from view.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] It is ideal for first-person 3D games, for example.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] More than that, the API is useful for any applications that require significant mouse input to control movements, rotate objects, and change entries, for example allowing users to control the viewing angle by moving the mouse around without any button clicking.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The buttons are then freed up for other actions.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Other examples include apps for viewing maps or satellite imagery.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Pointer lock lets you access mouse events even when the cursor goes past the boundary of the browser or screen.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] For example, your users can continue to rotate or manipulate a 3D model by moving the mouse without end.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Without Pointer lock, the rotation or manipulation stops the moment the pointer reaches the edge of the browser or screen.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Game players can now click buttons and swipe the mouse cursor back and forth without worrying about leaving the game play area and accidentally clicking another application that would take mouse focus away from the game.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Pointer lock is related to pointer capture.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Pointer capture provides continued delivery of events to a target element while a mouse is being dragged, but it stops when the mouse button is released.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] This section provides a brief description of each property and method related to the pointer lock specification.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The Pointer lock API, similar to the Fullscreen API, extends DOM elements by adding a new method, `requestPointerLock()`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Operating systems enable mouse acceleration by default, which is useful when you sometimes want slow precise movement (think about you might use a graphics package), but also want to move great distances with a faster mouse movement (think about scrolling, and selecting several files).
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] For some first-person perspective games however, raw mouse input data is preferred for controlling camera rotation — where the same distance movement, fast or slow, results in the same rotation.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] This results in a better gaming experience and higher accuracy, according to professional gamers.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The `pointerLockElement` property is useful for determining if any element is currently pointer locked (e.g., for doing a boolean check) and also for obtaining a reference to the locked element, if any.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The `Document.exitPointerLock()` method is used to exit pointer lock, and like `requestPointerLock`, works asynchronously using the `pointerlockchange` and `pointerlockerror` events, which you'll see more about below.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] When the Pointer lock state changes—for example, when calling `requestPointerLock()` or `exitPointerLock()`, the user pressing the ESC key, etc.—the `pointerlockchange` event is dispatched to the `document`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] This is a simple event containing no extra data.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] When there is an error caused by calling `requestPointerLock()` or `exitPointerLock()`, the `pointerlockerror` event is dispatched to the `document`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The Pointer lock API extends the normal `MouseEvent` interface with movement attributes.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Two new attributes to mouse events—`movementX` and `movementY`—provide the change in mouse positions.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The values of the parameters are the same as the difference between the values of `MouseEvent` properties, `screenX` and `screenY`, which are stored in two subsequent `mousemove` events, `eNow` and `ePrevious`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] In other words, the Pointer lock parameter `movementX = eNow.screenX - ePrevious.screenX`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] When Pointer lock is enabled, the standard `MouseEvent` properties `clientX`, `clientY`, `screenX`, and `screenY` are held constant, as if the mouse is not moving.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The `movementX` and `movementY` properties continue to provide the mouse's change in position.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] There is no limit to `movementX` and `movementY` values if the mouse is continuously moving in a single direction.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The concept of the mouse cursor does not exist and the cursor cannot move off the window or be clamped by a screen edge.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The parameters `movementX` and `movementY` are valid regardless of the mouse lock state, and are available even when unlocked for convenience.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] When the mouse is unlocked, the system cursor can exit and re-enter the browser window.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] If that happens, `movementX` and `movementY` could be set to zero.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] We've written a pointer lock demo (see source code) to show you how to use it to set up a simple control system.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] This demo uses JavaScript to draw a ball on top of a `<canvas>` element.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] When you click the canvas, pointer lock is then used to remove the mouse pointer and allow you to move the ball directly using the mouse.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Next we set up an event listener to run the `requestPointerLock()` method on the canvas when it is clicked, which initiates pointer lock.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The `document.pointerLockElement` check is to see if there is already an active pointer lock — we don't want to keep calling `requestPointerLock()` on the canvas every time we click inside it if we already have pointer lock.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Now for the dedicated pointer lock event listener: `pointerlockchange`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] When this occurs, we run a function called `lockChangeAlert()` to handle the change.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] This function checks the `pointerLockElement` property to see if it is our canvas.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] If so, it attached an event listener to handle the mouse movements with the `updatePosition()` function.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] If not, it removes the event listener again.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] The `updatePosition()` function updates the position of the ball on the canvas (`x` and `y`), and also includes `if ()` statements to check whether the ball has gone off the edges of the canvas.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] If so, it makes the ball wrap around to the opposite edge.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] It also includes a check whether a `requestAnimationFrame()` call has previously been made, and if so, calls it again as required, and calls the `canvasDraw()` function that updates the canvas scene.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] A tracker is also set up to write out the X and Y values to the screen, for reference.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] Pointer lock can only lock one `<iframe>` at a time.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] If you lock one `<iframe>`, you can't lock another one and transfer the target to it; pointer lock will error out.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] To avoid this limitation, first unlock the locked `<iframe>`, and then lock the other.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] While `<iframe>` work by default, "sandboxed" `<iframe>`s block Pointer lock.
[src:pointer-lock/pointer-lock-api] To avoid this limitation, use `<iframe sandbox="allow-pointer-lock">`.
[src:pointer-lock/pointerlockchange-event] The **`pointerlockchange`** event is fired when the pointer is locked/unlocked.
[src:pointer-lock/pointerlockchange-event] The event handler can use `Document.pointerLockElement` to determine whether the pointer is locked, and if so, to which element it is locked.
[src:pointer-lock/pointerlockchange-event] This event is not cancelable and does not bubble.
[src:pointer-lock/pointerlockchange-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] The **`requestPointerLock()`** method of the `Element` interface lets you asynchronously ask for the pointer to be locked on the given element.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] To track the success or failure of the request, it is necessary to listen for the `pointerlockchange` and `pointerlockerror` events at the `Document` level.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] Disables OS-level adjustment for mouse acceleration, and accesses raw mouse input instead.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] The default value is `false`; setting it to `true` will disable mouse acceleration.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] A `Promise` that resolves with `undefined`.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] Transient activation is required when calling `requestPointerLock()`.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] The user has to interact with the page or a UI element in order for this feature to work.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] Also, the target element's associated document must be in the active state.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] If calling `requestPointerLock()` immediately after releasing the pointer lock via the default unlock gesture (instead of through an `exitPointerLock()` call), the call will fail, even if a transient activation is available.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] If calling `requestPointerLock()` with `requestFullscreen()`, the `requestPointerLock()` must be called first, because the `requestFullscreen()` will consume the state of transient activation.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] The `allow-pointer-lock` sandbox token must be added when calling `requestPointerLock()` in an `<iframe>` element.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] Also, no other elements in other `<iframe>` elements may be in pointer lock mode.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] Pointer lock is often used in online games, when you want your mouse movement to be focused on controlling the game, without the distraction of the mouse pointer moving around, going outside the game area, or reaching the edge of the window.
[src:pointer-lock/requestpointerlock] To enable pointer lock, you would get the user to interact with the UI in some way, perhaps by pressing a button, or the game canvas itself.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most modern video games are audiovisual, with audio complement delivered through speakers or headphones, and sometimes also with other types of sensory feedback (e.g., haptic technology that provides tactile sensations).
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Some video games also allow microphone and webcam inputs for in-game chatting and livestreaming.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video games are typically categorized according to their hardware platform, which traditionally includes arcade video games, console games, and computer games (which includes LAN games, online games, and browser games).
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] More recently, the video game industry has expanded onto mobile gaming through mobile devices (such as smartphones and tablet computers), virtual and augmented reality systems, and remote cloud gaming.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video games are also classified into a wide range of genres based on their style of gameplay and target audience.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The first video game prototypes in the 1950s and 1960s were simple extensions of electronic games using video-like output from large, room-sized mainframe computers.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The first consumer video game was the arcade video game *Computer Space* in 1971, which took inspiration from the earlier 1962 computer game *Spacewar!*.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In 1972 came the now-iconic video game *Pong* and the first home console, the Magnavox Odyssey.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The industry grew quickly during the "golden age" of arcade video games from the late 1970s to early 1980s but suffered from the crash of the North American video game market in 1983 due to loss of publishing control and saturation of the market.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Following the crash, the industry matured, was dominated by Japanese companies such as Nintendo, Sega, and Sony, and established practices and methods around the development and distribution of video games to prevent a similar crash in the future, many of which continue to be followed.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In the 2000s, the core industry centered on "AAA" games, leaving little room for riskier experimental games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Coupled with the availability of the Internet and digital distribution, this gave room for independent video game development (or "indie games") to gain prominence into the 2010s.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Since then, the commercial importance of the video game industry has been increasing.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The emerging Asian markets and proliferation of smartphone games in particular are altering player demographics towards casual and cozy gaming, and increasing monetization by incorporating games as a service.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Today, video game development requires numerous skills, vision, teamwork, and liaisons between different parties, including developers, publishers, distributors, retailers, hardware manufacturers, and other marketers, to successfully bring a game to its consumers.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The video game market is also a major influence behind the electronics industry, where personal computer component, console, and peripheral sales, as well as consumer demands for better game performance, have been powerful driving factors for hardware design and innovation.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Early video games used interactive electronic devices with various display formats.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The earliest example dates to 1947—a "cathode-ray tube amusement device" was filed for a patent on 25 January 1947, by Thomas T.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Goldsmith Jr. and Estle Ray Mann, and issued on 14 December 1948, as U.S.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Inspired by radar display technology, it consisted of an analog device allowing a user to control the parabolic arc of a dot on the screen to simulate a missile being fired at targets, which were paper drawings fixed to the screen.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Other early examples include the Nimrod computer at the 1951 Festival of Britain; Christopher Strachey's *Checkers*, possibly the first game to display visuals on an electronic screen in 1952; *OXO*, a tic-tac-toe computer game by Alexander S.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Douglas for the EDSAC in 1952; *Tennis for Two*, an electronic interactive game engineered by William Higinbotham in 1958; and *Spacewar!*, written by Massachusetts Institute of Technology students Martin Graetz, Steve Russell, and Wayne Wiitanen's on a DEC PDP-1 computer in 1962.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These inventions laid the foundation for modern video games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In 1966, while working at Sanders Associates, Ralph H.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Baer devised a system to play a basic table tennis game on a television screen.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] With the company's approval, Baer created the prototype known as the "Brown Box".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Sanders patented Baer's innovations and licensed them to Magnavox, which commercialized the technology as the first home video game console, the Magnavox Odyssey, released in 1972.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Separately, Nolan Bushnell and Ted Dabney, inspired by seeing *Spacewar!* running at Stanford University, devised a similar version running in a smaller coin-operated arcade cabinet using a less expensive computer.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This was released as *Computer Space*, the first arcade video game, in 1971.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Bushnell and Dabney went on to form Atari, Inc., and with Allan Alcorn, created their second arcade game in 1972, the hit ping pong-style *Pong*, which was directly inspired by the table tennis game on the Odyssey.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Atari made a home version of *Pong*, which was released by Christmas 1975.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The success of the Odyssey and *Pong*, both as an arcade game and home machine, launched the video game industry.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Both Baer and Bushnell have been titled "Father of Video Games" for their contributions.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The term "video game" was developed to describe electronic games played on a video display rather than on a teletype printer, audio speaker, or similar device.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This also distinguished from handheld electronic games such as *Merlin,* which commonly used LED lights for indicators not in combination for imaging purposes.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] "Computer game" may also be used as a descriptor, as all these types of games essentially require the use of a computer processor; in some cases, it is used interchangeably with "video game".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Particularly in the United Kingdom and Western Europe, this is common due to the historic relevance of domestically produced microcomputers.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Other terms used include digital game, for example, by the Australian Bureau of Statistics.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The term "computer game" can also refer to PC games, which are played primarily on personal computers or other flexible hardware systems, to distinguish them from console games, arcade games, or mobile games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Other terms, such as "television game", "telegame", or "TV game", had been used in the 1970s and early 1980s, particularly for home gaming consoles that rely on connection to a television set.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] However, these terms were also used interchangeably with "video game" in the 1970s, primarily due to "video" and "television" being synonymous.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In Japan, where consoles like the Odyssey were first imported and then made within the country by the large television manufacturers such as Toshiba and Sharp Corporation, such games are known as "TV games", "TV geemu", or "terebi geemu".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The term "TV game" is still commonly used into the 21st century.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] "Electronic game" may also be used to refer to video games, but this also incorporates devices like early handheld electronic games that lack any video output.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The first appearance of the term "video game" emerged around 1973.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The Oxford English Dictionary cited a 10 November 1973 *BusinessWeek* article as the first printed use of the term.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Though Bushnell believed the term came from a vending magazine review of *Computer Space* in 1971, a review of the major vending magazines *Vending Times* and *Cashbox* showed that the term may have come even earlier, appearing first in a letter dated July 10, 1972.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In the letter, Bushnell uses the term "video game" twice.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Per video game historian Keith Smith, the sudden appearance suggested that the term had been proposed and readily adopted by those in the field.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Around March 1973, Ed Adlum, who ran *Cashbox*'s coin-operated section until 1972 and then later founded *RePlay Magazine*, covering the coin-op amusement field, in 1975, used the term in an article in March 1973.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In a September 1982 issue of *RePlay*, Adlum is credited with first naming these games as "video games": "RePlay's Eddie Adlum worked at 'Cash Box' when 'TV games' first came out.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The personalities in those days were Bushnell, his sales manager Pat Karns, and a handful of other 'TV game' manufacturers like Henry Leyser and the McEwan brothers.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] With the arrival of video games in arcades during the early 1970s, there was initially some confusion in the arcade industry over what term should be used to describe the new games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] While many games readily fall into a clear, well-understood definition of video games, new genres and innovations in game development have raised the question of what are the essential factors of a video game that separate the medium from other forms of entertainment.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The introduction of interactive films in the 1980s with games like *Dragon's Lair*, featured games with full motion video played off a form of media but only limited user interaction.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This had required a means to distinguish these games from more traditional board games that happen to also use external media, such as the *Clue VCR Mystery Game* which required players to watch VCR clips between turns.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] To distinguish between these two, video games are considered to require some interactivity that affects the visual display.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most video games tend to feature some type of victory or winning conditions, such as a scoring mechanism or a final boss fight.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These are still commonly justified as video games as they provide a game world that the player can interact with by some means.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The lack of any industry definition for a video game by 2021 was an issue during the case *Epic Games v.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Apple* which dealt with video games offered on Apple's iOS App Store.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Among concerns raised were games like *Fortnite Creative* and *Roblox* which created metaverses of interactive experiences, and whether the larger game and the individual experiences themselves were games or not in relation to fees that Apple charged for the App Store.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Rogers still concluded that what is a video game "appears highly eclectic and diverse".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The gameplay experience varies radically between video games, but many common elements exist.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most games will launch into a title screen and give the player a chance to review options such as the number of players before starting a game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most games are divided into levels which the player must work the avatar through, scoring points, collecting power-ups to boost the avatar's innate attributes, all while either using special attacks to defeat enemies or moves to avoid them.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This information is relayed to the player through a type of on-screen user interface such as a heads-up display atop the rendering of the game itself.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Taking damage will deplete their avatar's health, and if that falls to zero or if the avatar otherwise falls into an impossible-to-escape location, the player will lose one of their lives.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Should they lose all their lives without gaining an extra life or "1-UP", then the player will reach the "game over" screen.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Many levels as well as the game's finale end with a type of boss character the player must defeat to continue on.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In some games, intermediate points between levels will offer save points where the player can create a saved game on storage media to restart the game should they lose all their lives or need to stop the game and restart at a later time.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These also may be in the form of a passage that can be written down and reentered at the title screen.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Product flaws include software bugs which can manifest as glitches which may be exploited by the player; this is often the foundation of speedrunning a video game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These bugs, along with cheat codes, Easter eggs, and other hidden secrets that were intentionally added to the game can also be exploited.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] On some consoles, cheat cartridges allow players to execute these cheat codes, and user-developed trainers allow similar bypassing for computer software games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Both of which might make the game easier, give the player additional power-ups, or change the appearance of the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] To distinguish from electronic games, a video game is generally considered to require a platform, the hardware which contains computing elements, to process player interaction from some type of input device and displays the results to a video output display.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video games require a platform, a specific combination of electronic components or computer hardware and associated software, to operate.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These platforms may include multiple brandsheld by platform holders, such as Nintendo or Sony, seeking to gain larger market shares.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Games are typically designed to be played on one or a limited number of platforms, and exclusivity to a platform or brand is used by platform holders as a competitive edge in the video game market.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] However, games may be developed for alternative platforms than intended, which are described as ports or conversions.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These also may be remasters - where most of the original game's source code is reused and art assets, models, and game levels are updated for modern systems – and remakes, where in addition to asset improvements, significant reworking of the original game and possibly from scratch is performed.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The list below is not exhaustive and excludes other electronic devices capable of playing video games such as PDAs and graphing calculators.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Personal computers are not dedicated game platforms, so there may be differences running the same game on different hardware.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] (in which a person plays a video game with people who are in a different household) and others.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] is a PC or laptop intended specifically for gaming, typically using high-performance, high-cost components.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] and other similarly shared systems, with users logging in remotely to use the computer.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] A console game is played on a home console, a specialized electronic device that connects to a common television set or composite video monitor.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Home consoles are specifically designed to play games using a dedicated hardware environment, giving developers a concrete hardware target for development and assurances of what features will be available, simplifying development compared to PC game development.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Usually consoles only run games developed for it, or games from other platform made by the same company, but never games developed by its direct competitor, even if the same game is available on different platforms.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] It often comes with a specific game controller.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Major console platforms include Xbox, PlayStation and Nintendo.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] is a small, self-contained electronic device that is portable and can be held in a user's hands.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Like consoles, handhelds are dedicated platforms, and share almost the same characteristics.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Handheld hardware usually is less powerful than PC or console hardware.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Some handheld games from the late 1970s and early 1980s could only play one game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In the 1990s and 2000s, a number of handheld games used cartridges, which enabled them to be used to play many different games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The handheld console has waned in the 2010s as mobile device gaming has become a more dominant factor.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Arcade games often have brightly painted logos and images relating to the theme of the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] While most arcade games are housed in a vertical cabinet, which the user typically stands in front of to play, some arcade games use a tabletop approach, in which the display screen is housed in a table-style cabinet with a see-through table top.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] With table-top games, the users typically sit to play.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In the 1990s and 2000s, some arcade games offered players a choice of multiple games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In the 1980s, video arcades were businesses in which game players could use a number of arcade video games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In the 2010s, there are far fewer video arcades, but some movie theaters and family entertainment centers still have them.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] requires a minimal hardware device, such as a basic computer, console, laptop, mobile phone or even a dedicated hardware device connected to a display with good Internet connectivity that connects to hardware systems by the cloud gaming provider.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] between player input and output on their display device.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] to immerse a player within virtual environment that responds to their head movements.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Some VR systems include control units for the player's hands as to provide a direct way to interact with the virtual world.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] VR systems generally require a separate computer, console, or other processing device that couples with the head-mounted unit.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] on a modern system, simulating the hardware of the original and allows old games to be played.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] While emulators themselves have been found to be legal in United States case law, the act of obtaining the game software that one does not already own may violate copyrights.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] is similar in nature to emulation in that older games can be played on newer platforms, but typically directly though hardware and built-in software within the platform.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Early arcade games, home consoles, and handheld games were dedicated hardware units with the game's logic built into the electronic componentry of the hardware.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Since then, most video game platforms are considered programmable, having means to read and play multiple games distributed on different types of media or formats.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Physical formats include ROM cartridges, magnetic storage including magnetic-tape data storage and floppy discs, optical media formats including CD-ROM and DVDs, and flash memory cards.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Furthermore digital distribution over the Internet or other communication methods as well as cloud gaming alleviate the need for any physical media.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In some cases, the media serves as the direct read-only memory for the game, or it may be the form of installation media that is used to write the main assets to the player's platform's local storage for faster loading periods and later updates.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Games can be extended with new content and software patches through either expansion packs which are typically available as physical media, or as downloadable content nominally available via digital distribution.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These can be offered freely or can be used to monetize a game following its initial release.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Several games offer players the ability to create user-generated content to share with others to play.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Other games, mostly those on personal computers, can be extended with user-created modifications or mods that alter or add onto the game; these often are unofficial and were developed by players from reverse engineering of the game, but other games provide official support for modding the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video game can use several types of input devices to translate human actions to a game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most common are the use of game controllers like gamepads and joysticks for most consoles, and as accessories for personal computer systems along keyboard and mouse controls.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Common controls on the most recent controllers include face buttons, shoulder triggers, analog sticks, and directional pads ("d-pads").
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Consoles typically include standard controllers which are shipped or bundled with the console itself, while peripheral controllers are available as a separate purchase from the console manufacturer or third-party vendors.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Similar control sets are built into handheld consoles and onto arcade cabinets.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Newer technology improvements have incorporated additional technology into the controller or the game platform, such as touchscreens and motion detection sensors that give more options for how the player interacts with the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Specialized controllers may be used for certain genres of games, including racing wheels, light guns and dance pads.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Digital cameras and motion detection can capture movements of the player as input into the game, which can, in some cases, effectively eliminate the control, and on other systems such as virtual reality, are used to enhance immersion into the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] By definition, all video games are intended to output graphics to an external video display, such as cathode ray tube televisions, newer liquid-crystal display (LCD) televisions and built-in screens, projectors or computer monitors, depending on the type of platform the game is played on.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Features such as color depth, refresh rate, frame rate, and screen resolution are a combination of the limitations of the game platform and display device and the program efficiency of the game itself.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The game's output can range from fixed displays using LED or LCD elements, text-based games, two-dimensional and three-dimensional graphics, and augmented reality displays.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The game's graphics are often accompanied by sound produced by internal speakers on the game platform or external speakers attached to the platform, as directed by the game's programming.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This often will include sound effects tied to the player's actions to provide audio feedback, as well as background music for the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Some platforms support additional feedback mechanics to the player that a game can take advantage of.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This is most commonly haptic technology built into the game controller, such as causing the controller to shake in the player's hands to simulate a shaking earthquake occurring in game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video games are frequently classified by a number of factors related to how one plays them.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] A video game, like most other forms of media, may be categorized into genres.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] However, unlike film or television which use visual or narrative elements, video games are generally categorized into genres based on their gameplay interaction, since this is the primary means which one interacts with a video game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The narrative setting does not impact gameplay; a shooter game is still a shooter game, regardless of whether it takes place in a fantasy world or in outer space.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] An exception is the horror game genre, used for games that are based on narrative elements of horror fiction, the supernatural, and psychological horror.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The names may shift over time as players, developers and the media come up with new terms; for example, first-person shooters were originally called "Doom clones" based on the 1993 game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] A hierarchy of game genres exist, with top-level genres like "shooter game" and "action game" that broadly capture the game's main gameplay style, and several subgenres of specific implementation, such as within the shooter game first-person shooter and third-person shooter.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Some cross-genre types also exist that fall until multiple top-level genres such as action-adventure game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] A video game's mode describes how many players can use the game at the same type.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This is primarily distinguished by single-player video games and multiplayer video games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Within the latter category, multiplayer games can be played in a variety of ways, including locally at the same device, on separate devices connected through a local network such as LAN parties, or online via separate Internet connections.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most multiplayer games are based on competitive gameplay, but many offer cooperative and team-based options as well as asymmetric gameplay.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Online games use server structures that can also enable massively multiplayer online games (MMOs) to support hundreds of players at the same time.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] A small number of video games are zero-player games, in which the player has very limited interaction with the game itself.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These are most commonly simulation games where the player may establish a starting state and then let the game proceed on its own, watching the results as a passive observer, such as with many computerized simulations of Conway's Game of Life.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most video games are intended for entertainment purposes.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Core or hard-core games refer to the typical perception of video games, developed for entertainment purposes.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These games typically require a fair amount of time to learn and master, in contrast to casual games, and thus are most appealing to gamers rather than a broader audience.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most of the AAA video game industry is based around the delivery of core games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] They frequently support the ability to jump in and out of play on demand, such as during commuting or lunch breaks.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] mechanics, where players can enlist the help of friends on their social media networks for extra turns or moves each day.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] has been used in homes and classrooms to help teach children and students, and video games have been similarly adapted for these reasons, all designed to provide a form of interactivity and entertainment tied to game design elements.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] There are a variety of differences in their designs and how they educate the user.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] that are geared towards problem solving through motivation and positive reinforcement while downplaying the entertainment value.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] are those where the entertainment factor may be augmented, overshadowed, or even eliminated by other purposes for the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Although video games have been considered an art form on their own, games may be developed to try to purposely communicate a story or message, using the medium as a work of art.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] are designed to generate emotion and empathy from the player by challenging societal norms and offering critique through the interactivity of the video game medium.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] They may not have any type of win condition and are designed to let the player explore through the game world and scenarios.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] in nature, designed based on personal experiences or stories through a single developer or small team.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video games can be subject to national and international content rating requirements.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Like with film content ratings, video game ratings typing identify the target age group that the national or regional ratings board believes is appropriate for the player, ranging from all-ages, to a teenager-or-older, to mature, to the infrequent adult-only games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most content review is based on the level of violence, both in the type of violence and how graphic it may be represented, and sexual content, but other themes such as drug and alcohol use and gambling that can influence children may also be identified.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] A primary identifier based on a minimum age is used by nearly all systems, along with additional descriptors to identify specific content that players and parents should be aware of.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The regulations vary from country to country but generally are voluntary systems upheld by vendor practices, with penalty and fines issued by the ratings body on the video game publisher for misuse of the ratings.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Certain nations have even more restrictive rules related to political or ideological content.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Within Germany, until 2018, the Unterhaltungssoftware Selbstkontrolle (*Entertainment Software Self-Regulation*) would refuse to classify, and thus allow sale, of any game depicting Nazi imagery, and thus often requiring developers to replace such imagery with fictional ones.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This ruling was relaxed in 2018 to allow for such imagery for "social adequacy" purposes that applied to other works of art.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] China's video game segment is mostly isolated from the rest of the world due to the government's censorship, and all games published there must adhere to strict government review, disallowing content such as smearing the image of the Chinese Communist Party.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Foreign games published in China often require modification by developers and publishers to meet these requirements.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video game development and authorship, much like any other form of entertainment, is frequently a cross-disciplinary field.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video game developers, as employees within this industry are commonly referred to, primarily include programmers and graphic designers.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Over the years, this has expanded to include almost every type of skill that one might see prevalent in the creation of any movie or television program, including sound designers, musicians, and other technicians; as well as skills that are specific to video games, such as the game designer.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In the early days of the industry, it was more common for a single person to manage all of the roles needed to create a video game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] As platforms have become more complex and powerful in the type of material they can present, larger teams have been needed to generate all of the art, programming, cinematography, and more.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Video games are programmed like any other piece of computer software.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Prior to the mid-1970s, arcade and home consoles were programmed by assembling discrete electro-mechanical components on circuit boards, which limited games to relatively simple logic.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] By 1975, low-cost microprocessors were available at volume to be used for video game hardware, which allowed game developers to program more detailed games, widening the scope of what was possible.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Ongoing improvements in computer hardware technology have expanded what has become possible to create in video games, coupled with convergence of common hardware between console, computer, and arcade platforms to simplify the development process.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Today, game developers have a number of commercial and open source tools available for use to make games, often which are across multiple platforms to support portability, or may still opt to create their own for more specialized features and direct control of the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Today, many games are built around a game engine that handles the bulk of the game's logic, gameplay, and rendering.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These engines can be augmented with specialized engines for specific features, such as a physics engine that simulates the physics of objects in real-time.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] A variety of middleware exists to help developers access other features, such as playback of videos within games, network-oriented code for games that communicate via online services, matchmaking for online games, and similar features.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] These features can be used from a developer's programming language of choice, or they may opt to also use game development kits that minimize the amount of direct programming they have to do but can also limit the amount of customization they can add into a game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Like all software, video games usually undergo quality testing before release to assure there are no bugs or glitches in the product, though frequently developers will release patches and updates.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] With the growth of the size of development teams in the industry, the problem of cost has increased.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Development studios need the best talent, while publishers reduce costs to maintain profitability on their investment.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Typically, a video game console development team ranges from 5 to 50 people, and some exceed 100.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In May 2009, *Assassin's Creed II* was reported to have a development staff of 450.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The growth of team size combined with greater pressure to get completed projects into the market to begin recouping production costs has led to a greater occurrence of missed deadlines, rushed games, and the release of unfinished products.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] While amateur and hobbyist game programming had existed since the late 1970s with the introduction of home computers, a newer trend since the mid-2000s is indie game development.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Indie games are made by small teams outside any direct publisher control, their games being smaller in scope than those from the larger "AAA" game studios, and are often experiments in gameplay and art style.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Indie game development is aided by the larger availability of digital distribution, including the newer mobile gaming market, and readily-available and low-cost development tools for these platforms.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Although departments of computer science have been studying technical aspects of video games for years, theories that examine games as an artistic medium are a relatively recent development.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The two most visible schools in this field are ludology and narratology.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Narrativists approach video games in the context of what Janet Murray calls "Cyberdrama".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] That is to say, their major concern is with video games as a storytelling medium, one that arises out of interactive fiction.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Murray puts video games in the context of the Holodeck, a fictional piece of technology from *Star Trek*, arguing for the video game as a medium in which the player is allowed to become another person, and to act out in another world.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This image of video games received early widespread popular support, and forms the basis of films such as *Tron*, *eXistenZ* and *The Last Starfighter*.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Ludologists break sharply and radically from this idea.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] They argue that a video game is first and foremost a game, which must be understood in terms of its rules, interface, and the concept of play that it deploys.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Espen Aarseth argues that, although games certainly have plots, characters, and aspects of traditional narratives, these aspects are incidental to gameplay.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] While many games rely on emergent principles, video games commonly present simulated story worlds where emergent behavior occurs within the context of the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The term "emergent narrative" has been used to describe how, in a simulated environment, storyline can be created simply by "what happens to the player." However, emergent behavior is not limited to sophisticated games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] In general, any place where event-driven instructions occur for AI in a game, emergent behavior will exist.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] For instance, take a racing game in which cars are programmed to avoid crashing, and they encounter an obstacle in the track: the cars might then maneuver to avoid the obstacle causing the cars behind them to slow or maneuver to accommodate the cars in front of them and the obstacle.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The programmer never wrote code to specifically create a traffic jam, yet one now exists in the game.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Most commonly, video games are protected by copyright, though both patents and trademarks have been used as well.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Though local copyright regulations vary to the degree of protection, video games qualify as copyrighted visual-audio works, and enjoy cross-country protection under the Berne Convention.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] This typically only applies to the underlying code, as well as to the artistic aspects of the game such as its writing, art assets, and music.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Because gameplay is normally ineligible for copyright, gameplay ideas in popular games are often replicated and built upon in other games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] At times, this repurposing of gameplay can be seen as beneficial and a fundamental part of how the industry has grown by building on the ideas of others.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] For example *Doom* (1993) and *Grand Theft Auto III* (2001) introduced gameplay that created popular new game genres, the first-person shooter and the *Grand Theft Auto* clone, respectively, in the few years after their release.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] However, at times and more frequently at the onset of the industry, developers would intentionally create video game clones of successful games and game hardware with few changes, which led to the flooded arcade and dedicated home console market around 1978.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] Cloning is also a major issue with countries that do not have strong intellectual property protection laws, such as within China.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The lax oversight by China's government and the difficulty for foreign companies to take Chinese entities to court had enabled China to support a large grey market of cloned hardware and software systems.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p01] The industry remains challenged to distinguish between creating new games based on refinements of past successful games to create a new type of gameplay, and intentionally creating a clone of a game that may simply swap out art assets.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The early history of the video game industry, following the first game hardware releases and through 1983, had little structure.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video games quickly took off during the golden age of arcade video games from the late 1970s to early 1980s, but the newfound industry was mainly composed of game developers with little business experience.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] This led to numerous companies forming simply to create clones of popular games to try to capitalize on the market.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Due to loss of publishing control and oversaturation of the market, the North American home video game market crashed in 1983, dropping from revenues of around $3 billion in 1983 to $100 million by 1985.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Many of the North American companies created in the prior years closed down.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Japan's growing game industry was briefly shocked by this crash but had sufficient longevity to withstand the short-term effects, and Nintendo helped to revitalize the industry with the release of the Nintendo Entertainment System in North America in 1985.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Along with it, Nintendo established a number of core industrial practices to prevent unlicensed game development and control game distribution on their platform, methods that continue to be used by console manufacturers today.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The industry remained more conservative following the 1983 crash, forming around the concept of publisher-developer dichotomies, and by the 2000s, leading to the industry centralizing around low-risk, triple-A games and studios with large development budgets of at least $10 million or more.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video games have a large network effect that draw on many different sectors that tie into the larger video game industry.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The industry itself grew out from both the United States and Japan in the 1970s and 1980s before having a larger worldwide contribution.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Today, the video game industry is predominantly led by major companies in North America (primarily the United States and Canada), Europe, and southeast Asia including Japan, South Korea, and China.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Hardware production remains an area dominated by Asian companies either directly involved in hardware design or part of the production process, but digital distribution and indie game development of the late 2000s has allowed game developers to flourish nearly anywhere and diversify the field.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] According to the market research firm Newzoo, the global video game industry drew estimated revenues of over $159 billion in 2020.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Mobile games accounted for the bulk of this, with a 48% share of the market, followed by console games at 28% and personal computer games at 23%.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Sales of different types of games vary widely between countries due to local preferences.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Japanese consumers tend to purchase much more handheld games than console games and especially PC games, with a strong preference for games catering to local tastes.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Another key difference is that, though having declined in the West, arcade games remain an important sector of the Japanese gaming industry.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] In South Korea, computer games are generally preferred over console games, especially MMORPG games and real-time strategy games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Computer games are also popular in China.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video game culture is a worldwide new media subculture formed around video games and game playing.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] As computer and video games have increased in popularity over time, they have had a significant influence on popular culture.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video game culture has also evolved over time hand in hand with internet culture as well as the increasing popularity of mobile games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Many people who play video games identify as gamers, which can mean anything from someone who enjoys games to someone who is passionate about it.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] As video games become more social with multiplayer and online capability, gamers find themselves in growing social networks.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Gaming can both be entertainment as well as competition, as a new trend known as electronic sports is becoming more widely accepted.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] In the 2010s, video games and discussions of video game trends and topics can be seen in social media, politics, television, film and music.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic during 2020–2021 gave further visibility to video games as a pastime to enjoy with friends and family online as a means of social distancing.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Since the mid-2000s there has been debate whether video games qualify as art, primarily as the form's interactivity interfered with the artistic intent of the work and that they are designed for commercial appeal.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] A significant debate on the matter came after film critic Roger Ebert published an essay "Video Games can never be art", which challenged the industry to prove him and other critics wrong.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The view that video games were an art form was cemented in 2011 when the U.S.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Supreme Court ruled in the landmark case *Brown v.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Entertainment Merchants Association* that video games were a protected form of speech with artistic merit.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video games will inspire sequels and other video games within the same franchise, but also have influenced works outside of the video game medium.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Numerous television shows (both animated and live-action), films, comics and novels have been created based on existing video game franchises.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Because video games are an interactive medium there has been trouble in converting them to these passive forms of media, and typically such works have been critically panned or treated as children's media.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] That said, some early video game-based films have been highly successful at the box office, such as 1995's *Mortal Kombat* and 2001's *Lara Croft: Tomb Raider*.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] More recently since the 2000s, there has also become a larger appreciation of video game music, which ranges from chiptunes composed for limited sound-output devices on early computers and consoles, to fully-scored compositions for most modern games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Such music has frequently served as a platform for covers and remixes, and concerts featuring video game soundtracks performed by bands or orchestras, such as *Video Games Live*, have also become popular.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video games also frequently incorporate licensed music, particularly in the area of rhythm games, furthering the depth of which video games and music can work together.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Further, video games can serve as a virtual environment under full control of a producer to create new works.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] With the capability to render 3D actors and settings in real-time, a new type of work machinima (short for "machine cinema") grew out from using video game engines to craft narratives.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] As video game engines gain higher fidelity, they have also become part of the tools used in more traditional filmmaking.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Unreal Engine has been used as a backbone by Industrial Light & Magic for their StageCraft technology for shows like *The Mandalorian*.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Separately, video games are also frequently used as part of the promotion and marketing for other media, such as for films, anime, and comics.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] However, these licensed games in the 1990s and 2000s often had a reputation for poor quality, developed without any input from the intellectual property rights owners, and several of them are considered among lists of games with notably negative reception, such as *Superman 64*.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] More recently, with these licensed games being developed by triple-A studios or through studios directly connected to the licensed property owner, there has been a significant improvement in the quality of these games, with an early trendsetting example of *Batman: Arkham Asylum*.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Besides their entertainment value, appropriately-designed video games have been seen to provide value in education across several ages and comprehension levels.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Learning principles found in video games have been identified as possible techniques with which to reform the U.S. education system.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] It has been noticed that gamers adopt an attitude while playing that is of such high concentration, they do not realize they are learning, and that if the same attitude could be adopted at school, education would enjoy significant benefits.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Students are found to be "learning by doing" while playing video games while fostering creative thinking.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video games are also believed to be beneficial to the mind and body.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] It has been shown that action video game players have better hand–eye coordination and visuo-motor skills, such as their resistance to distraction, their sensitivity to information in the peripheral vision and their ability to count briefly presented objects, than nonplayers.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Researchers found that such enhanced abilities could be acquired by training with action games, involving challenges that switch attention between different locations, but not with games requiring concentration on single objects.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] A 2018 systematic review found evidence that video gaming training had positive effects on cognitive and emotional skills in the adult population, especially with young adults.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] A 2019 systematic review also added support for the claim that video games are beneficial to the brain, although the beneficial effects of video gaming on the brain differed by video games types.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Organisers of video gaming events, such as the organisers of the *D-Lux* video game festival in Dumfries, Scotland, have emphasised the positive aspects video games can have on mental health.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Organisers, mental health workers and mental health nurses at the event emphasised the relationships and friendships that can be built around video games and how playing games can help people learn about others as a precursor to discussing the person's mental health.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] A study in 2020 from Oxford University also suggested that playing video games can be a benefit to a person's mental health.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The report of 3,274 gamers, all over the age of 18, focused on the games Animal Crossing: New Horizons and Plants vs Zombies: Battle for Neighborville and used actual play-time data.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The report found that those that played more games tended to report greater "wellbeing".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Also in 2020, computer science professor Regan Mandryk of the University of Saskatchewan said her research also showed that video games can have health benefits such as reducing stress and improving mental health.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The university's research studied all age groups – "from pre-literate children through to older adults living in long term care homes" – with a main focus on 18 to 55-year-olds.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] A study of gamers attitudes towards gaming which was reported about in 2018 found that millennials use video games as a key strategy for coping with stress.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] In the study of 1,000 gamers, 55% said that it "helps them to unwind and relieve stress ... and half said they see the value in gaming as a method of escapism to help them deal with daily work pressures".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Video games have caused controversy since the 1970s.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Medical experts and mental health professionals have also raised concerned that video games may be addictive, and the World Health Organization has included "gaming disorder" in the 11th revision of its International Statistical Classification of Diseases.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Even with case law establishing that video games qualify as a protected art form, there has been pressure on the video game industry to keep their products in check to avoid over-excessive violence particularly for games aimed at younger children.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The industry as a whole has also dealt with issues related to gender, racial, and LGBTQ+ discrimination and mischaracterization of these minority groups in video games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] A further issue in the industry is related to working conditions, as development studios and publishers frequently use "crunch time", required extended working hours, in the weeks and months ahead of a game's release to assure on-time delivery.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Players of video games often maintain collections of games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] More recently there has been interest in retro gaming, focusing on games from the first decades.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Games in retail packaging in good shape have become collector's items for the early days of the industry, with some rare publications having gone for over US$100,000 as of 2020.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Separately, there is also concern about the preservation of video games, as both game media and the hardware to play them degrade over time.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Further, many of the game developers and publishers from the first decades no longer exist, so records of their games have disappeared.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Archivists and preservations have worked within the scope of copyright law to save these games as part of the cultural history of the industry.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] There are many video game museums around the world, including the National Videogame Museum in Frisco, Texas, which serves as the largest museum wholly dedicated to the display and preservation of the industry's most important artifacts.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] Europe hosts video game museums such as the Computer Games Museum in Berlin and the Museum of Soviet Arcade Machines in Moscow and Saint-Petersburg.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The Museum of Art and Digital Entertainment in Oakland, California is a dedicated video game museum focusing on playable exhibits of console and computer games.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The Video Game Museum of Rome is also dedicated to preserving video games and their history.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The Smithsonian Institution in Washington, DC has three video games on permanent display: *Pac-Man*, *Dragon's Lair*, and *Pong*.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] The Museum of Modern Art has added a total of 20 video games and one video game console to its permanent Architecture and Design Collection since 2012.
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] In 2012, the Smithsonian American Art Museum ran an exhibition on "The Art of Video Games".
[src:pointer-lock/video-game-p02] However, the reviews of the exhibit were mixed, including questioning whether video games belong in an art museum.
